title: For Sale:  CZ Dan Wesson 715 Revolver - .357 6” Stainless
postcontent:
New in Box with Factory Warranty…
The 715 is as it was before — designed and built to be the most accurate, rugged and versatile revolver on the market. Shipped with a 6″ barrel, the new shroud is designated the HV6, a heavy vent shroud profile that tames the .357’s recoil very well.The double action trigger is short and relatively light, while the single action is light and crisp. The target-like SA trigger pull made the Dan Wesson revolver a favorite among competitors and hunters, and the tradition continues in the 715.Barrel assemblies and grips are easily swapped by the shooter, and the 715 accepts grips and barrel/shroud assemblies from 15-2 model and newer revolvers.The original Dan Wesson revolver improved on the accuracy and service life of the traditional double action revolver design in a few ways. The tensioned barrel of the DW interchangeable barrel system enhances accuracy, pulling the barrel tight like a guitar string, enabling it to vibrate at the same frequency every time. The forward crane latch, located in front of the cylinder and paired with a rear ball detent helps to ensure proper cylinder/barrel alignment during firing. Superior to the rear locking designs of other revolvers, it adds to the accuracy of the 715.While the tensioned barrel definitely improves accuracy above other revolvers, it’s the consistent cylinder/barrel alignment that contributes most to the accuracy of the design.Additionally, the clockwise-rotating cylinder reduces stress on the crane, since it turns in the same direction the crane locks, prolonging service life and keeping everything tight. The 715’s frame is robust, built to handle the heaviest of factory loads.Each revolver is shipped in a custom Dan Wesson hard case. title: For Sale:  Rare Smith & Wesson 1st Model Ladysmith Pre War 22
postcontent: Smith & Wesson Pre-war 1st Model "Ladysmith" .22 Hand Ejector Double Action Revolver, chambered for .22 caliber Long "Black Powder" cartridges, and factory fitted with the 3 ½ inch barrel, with a rare factory blue finish. This rare and unique little revolver bearing serial number 3731 was manufactured about 1905 according to published Smith & Wesson production information. The example shown here in our auction photographs is in exceptinal factory original condition still retaining a majority of the factory applied blued metal finish throughout, with most of the finish loss being to the cylinder as with a lot of these early Ladysmith revolvers, it is more common than not, for the finish on the cylinders to disappear early on. The .22 cal. bore in the 3 1/2 inch round barrel, along with all 7 cylinder chambers, all have nice bright bores, with no pitting, the revolver still functions perfectly in both double & single action, still cycles excellent, has a nice firm lock up, and the forcing cone is also excellent, showing no evidence of damage. Even the case colors are still evident on the hammer and trigger. Most collectors will find this 111 year old Ladysmith very difficult to upgrade. This revolver has a 7 shot cylinder that was designed to fire .22 Long (Black Powder Only) cartridges. However we never suggest firing any Black Powder Era firearms, and this nice clean little Ladysmith revolver is absolutely no exception. Truth is, firing this little beauty could actually damage it... These petite little revolvers are very small, and the intricate parts are very delicate. It is our opinion that firing any 100+ year old gun, be it an antique, or any early vintage firearm of any kind is risky. However to fire one of these tiny little revolvers, no matter which design, or model type is never advisable without the proper ammo, and instruction given by a competent, certified, professional gunsmith. But again, we want to be perfectly clear,,, the revolver shown here in our auction photographs is still fully functional in every way. The simple fact that the gun is still fully functional after 100+ years is "exceedingly rare", and makes it a very neat historic collectable.
